→ ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : ℕ → Fin (n + 2) → ℝ) (y : Set ℕ → Fin (n + 2) → ℝ),\n      ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := by\n```\n\nWe need to construct a convex set C in ℝⁿ⁺², and functions x and y such that for all i and s, x i + y s ∈ C if and only if i ∈ s.\n\nTo construct such a set, we can take C to be the set of all points in ℝⁿ⁺² that are not in the positive orthant. That is, C = {x ∈ ℝⁿ⁺² | ∃ j, x j ≤ 0}. \n\nThis set is not convex, but its convex hull will have infinite VC dimension. \n\nLet's think more carefully. \n\nIf we take C = {x ∈ ℝⁿ⁺² | ∃ j, x j ≤ 0}, then C is the union of the half-spaces x_j ≤ 0 for each j. The convex hull of C will contain all points that can be formed by convex combinations of points in C. \n\nFor example, if we take n = 1, then C = {x ∈ ℝ² | x₁ ≤ 0 or x₂ ≤ 0}. The convex hull of this set is the entire plane except for the positive quadrant (x₁ > 0 and x₂ > 0). \n\nIt's known that the VC dimension of the set of all half-spaces in ℝⁿ is n+1. But if we take a more complex set, its convex hull can have higher VC dimension.\n\nIn fact, a key result in learning theory is that the VC dimension of the convex hull of a set is the same as the VC dimension of the set itself. So if we can find a set with infinite VC dimension, its convex hull will also have infinite VC dimension.\n\nSo, let's construct a set in ℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VC dimension. \n\nConsider the set C = {x ∈ ℝⁿ⁺² | x₁ ≤ 0 or x₂ ≤ 0 or ... or xₙ₊₂ ≤ 0}. This set is not convex. Let's compute its convex hull.\n\nThe convex hull of C will contain all points that can be written as convex combinations of points in C. \n\nFor example, if we take n = 1, then C = {x ∈ ℝ² | x₁ ≤ 0 or x₂ ≤ 0}. The convex hull of this set is the entire plane except for the positive quadrant (x₁ > 0 and x₂ > 0). But this set has infinite VC dimension because we can separate any subset of size n.\n\nIn general, for the set C = {x ∈ ℝⁿ⁺² | x₁ ≤ 0 or x₂ ≤ 0 or ... or xₙ₊₂ ≤ 0}, the convex hull will have in