      "\n\nWe can define a set C in ℝⁿ⁺² such that for any subset S of {0, 1, 2, ...}, there exists a point in C that is the sum of a point from S and a point from C. This will allow us to show that C has infinite VC dimension.\n\nLet's formalize this in Lean 4:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convex.Basic\nimport Mathlib.Data.Real.Basic\n\n/-!\n# VCₙ dimension of convex sets in ℝⁿ⁺¹, ℝⁿ⁺²\n\nIn the literature it is known that every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3,\nand there exists a convex set in ℝ³ with infinite VC dimension (even more strongly,\nwhich shatters an infinite set).\n\nThis file proves that every convex set in ℝⁿ has finite VCₙ dimension, constructs a convex set in\nℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension (even more strongly, which n-shatters an infinite set),\nand conjectures that every convex set in ℝⁿ⁺¹ has finite VCₙ dimension.\n-/\n\n/-! ### What's known -/\n\n/-- Every convex set in ℝ² has VC dimension at most 3. -/\nlemma vc_lt_four_of_convex_r2 {C : Set (Fin 2 → ℝ)} (hC : Convex ℝ C)\n    {x : Fin 4 → Fin 2 → ℝ} {y : Set (Fin 4) → Fin 2 → ℝ}\n    (hxy : ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s) : False := sorry\n\n/-- There exists a set of infinite VC dimension in ℝ³. -/\nlemma exists_convex_r3_vc_eq_infty :\n    ∃ (C : Set (Fin 3 → ℝ)) (hC : Convex ℝ C) (x : ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ) (y : Set ℕ → Fin 3 → ℝ),\n      ∀ i s, x i + y s ∈ C ↔ i ∈ s := sorry\n```\n\nWe need to prove the existence of a convex set in ℝⁿ⁺² with infinite VCₙ dimension. Let's think about how to construct such a set.\n\nIn the context, we have a similar problem for ℝ³, where a convex set with infinite VC dimension was constructed. The key idea was to use a set that can be \" shattered \" by a sequence of points in a way that requires infinite precision.\n\nIn ℝⁿ⁺², we need to construct a convex set that can n-shatter an infinite set. The approach will be similar to the one in ℝ³. Let's consider the following construction:\n\nWe can define a set C in ℝⁿ⁺² such that for any subset S